00:50:06.700 --> 00:50:09.604
differently, partly because
of their perspectives,

00:50:09.604 --> 00:50:11.270
but also partly because
they've absorbed

00:50:11.270 --> 00:50:13.640
different sets of source
material to different degrees.

00:50:13.640 --> 00:50:14.660
Right?

00:50:14.660 --> 00:50:16.505
So putting those
two things together,

00:50:16.505 --> 00:50:18.380
do you think the practice
of history, as it's

00:50:18.380 --> 00:50:20.990
done today can, survive
the explosion in the amount

00:50:20.990 --> 00:50:21.830
of source material?

00:50:21.830 --> 00:50:24.163
Is there going to be any one
that can absorb all of that

00:50:24.163 --> 00:50:24.920
and synthesize it?

00:50:24.920 --> 00:50:26.180
DAN CARLIN: It's
an old joke, but it

00:50:26.180 --> 00:50:27.770
concerns with the
difference between

00:50:27.770 --> 00:50:29.660
modern and ancient history.

00:50:29.660 --> 00:50:30.950
And someone once said--

00:50:30.950 --> 00:50:32.150
it may have been
one of my teachers--

00:50:32.150 --> 00:50:33.774
had said something
about that if you're

00:50:33.774 --> 00:50:35.870
a historian of
the ancient world,

00:50:35.870 --> 00:50:40.130
your job is to find
needles in haystacks,

00:50:40.130 --> 00:50:41.930
but there's almost no haystacks.

00:50:41.930 --> 00:50:44.510
Whereas your job as
a modern historian

00:50:44.510 --> 00:50:46.550
is, there are
haystacks everywhere,

00:50:46.550 --> 00:50:48.590
which haystack do you pick?

00:50:48.590 --> 00:50:50.240
I ran into the same
problem in news.

00:50:50.240 --> 00:50:53.150
Because I was in LA, and
when you open up the news

00:50:53.150 --> 00:50:56.780
file in Los Angeles on what to
cover that day, it's that big.

00:50:56.780 --> 00:51:00.110
And your job is to go,
no, no, no, no, no,

00:51:00.110 --> 00:51:01.850
and what makes the final cut.

00:51:01.850 --> 00:51:04.149
So then I get a job
in Western Oregon.

00:51:04.149 --> 00:51:06.440
And I show up, and I look at
the file the next, morning

00:51:06.440 --> 00:51:08.300
and there's one
piece of paper in it.

00:51:08.300 --> 00:51:09.890
And the entire job is different.

00:51:09.890 --> 00:51:12.080
Your job is to go find
news stories, as opposed

00:51:12.080 --> 00:51:12.830
to weeding down.

00:51:12.830 --> 00:51:14.690
So the historian's job
is the same problem.

00:51:14.690 --> 00:51:17.060
Where if you talk about a
historian 100 years from now,

00:51:17.060 --> 00:51:18.350
think of all the
podcasts that they're

00:51:18.350 --> 00:51:19.600
going to have to weed through.

00:51:19.600 --> 00:51:23.851
The blog posts, and-- so it's
not a needle in a haystack job

00:51:23.851 --> 00:51:24.350
anymore.

00:51:24.350 --> 00:51:26.870
It's oh my god, a field
full of haystacks, which one

00:51:26.870 --> 00:51:28.930
do you think the needle's in?

00:51:28.930 --> 00:51:31.970
And the process of selection
as a historian is often--

00:51:31.970 --> 00:51:33.239
not to speak for them--

00:51:33.239 --> 00:51:35.530
but is often concerned with
what they're talking about.

00:51:35.530 --> 00:51:38.090
So let's say you're doing the
history of the New York Yankees

00:51:38.090 --> 00:51:39.110
baseball team.

00:51:39.110 --> 00:51:41.510
OK, there's a
self-selection right there,

00:51:41.510 --> 00:51:43.040
that helps you
winnow things down.

00:51:43.040 --> 00:51:43.540
Right?

00:51:43.540 --> 00:51:46.225
So you found three haystacks,
and those are your haystacks.

00:51:46.225 --> 00:51:48.140
And you start working
within that realm.

00:51:48.140 --> 00:51:50.240
The problem is, is if
somebody's writing a history

00:51:50.240 --> 00:51:53.589
book on baseball, OK, there's
going to be crossover.

00:51:53.589 --> 00:51:55.130
But there also might
be disagreement.

00:51:55.130 --> 00:51:57.620
The guy writing specifically
about the New York Yankees

00:51:57.620 --> 00:52:02.439
may come up with ideas,
concepts, views, or conclusions

00:52:02.439 --> 00:52:03.980
that are different
from a guy looking

00:52:03.980 --> 00:52:06.470
at it on a more macro level,
with baseball history,

00:52:06.470 --> 00:52:08.021
in general.

00:52:08.021 --> 00:52:10.520
In my mind-- and I think this
is how historians would do it.

00:52:10.520 --> 00:52:11.853
I'm not going to speak for them.

00:52:11.853 --> 00:52:15.350
But, I mean, I think the collage
of all the different historians

00:52:15.350 --> 00:52:17.720
together-- this
mosaic, that if you

00:52:17.720 --> 00:52:19.730
add them all together--
helps give you

00:52:19.730 --> 00:52:22.200
a more 360 view of things.

00:52:22.200 --> 00:52:24.197
So that in the same
way today, I think

00:52:24.197 --> 00:52:26.030
if you're an intelligent
well-rounded person

00:52:26.030 --> 00:52:27.680
you're reading
multiple news sources.

00:52:27.680 --> 00:52:30.350
Hopefully from multiple angles,
and if you're really good,

00:52:30.350 --> 00:52:32.450
from multiple countries.

00:52:32.450 --> 00:52:35.600
Take that, and do the
same thing with history.

00:52:35.600 --> 00:52:39.320
Where you're saying, OK,
here's a Roman view of somebody

00:52:39.320 --> 00:52:41.410
who liked Julius Caesar
versus, Suetonius,

00:52:41.410 --> 00:52:43.070
who's a gossip
columnist who writes

00:52:43.070 --> 00:52:44.390
all the bad stuff about him.

00:52:44.390 --> 00:52:45.973
And you throw all
this stuff together,

00:52:45.973 --> 00:52:48.030
and you realize, OK, a
lot of this may be false.

00:52:48.030 --> 00:52:50.720
But when I look at the
mosaic and stand back

00:52:50.720 --> 00:52:53.390
from it, what does it convey?

00:52:53.390 --> 00:52:55.580
And so I think that's
a good way to describe,

00:52:55.580 --> 00:52:57.146
like when we do the
audio footnotes,

00:52:57.146 --> 00:52:58.520
but we'll give
you two historians

00:52:58.520 --> 00:52:59.650
who disagree about something.

00:52:59.650 --> 00:53:01.550
And the tendency is to go,
well what did I just learn?

00:53:01.550 --> 00:53:02.060
Right?

00:53:02.060 --> 00:53:02.780
One said it was black.

00:53:02.780 --> 00:53:03.620
The other said it was white.

00:53:03.620 --> 00:53:05.030
Did I really learn anything?

00:53:05.030 --> 00:53:08.360
But being able to understand
that two intelligent people

00:53:08.360 --> 00:53:09.860
who've looked at
the source material

00:53:09.860 --> 00:53:12.980
came to different
conclusions is, in of itself,

00:53:12.980 --> 00:53:15.796
a useful piece of
information for you today.

00:53:15.796 --> 00:53:16.670
Does that make sense?

00:53:16.670 --> 00:53:17.180
AUDIENCE: Mm-hmm.

00:53:17.180 --> 00:53:19.763
DAN CARLIN: I mean, if 500 years
from now, the historians have

00:53:19.763 --> 00:53:24.140
to try to figure out
21st century US politics,

00:53:24.140 --> 00:53:29.600
and all they have to go on is an
MSNBC feed and a Fox News feed,

00:53:29.600 --> 00:53:32.180
you're going to have to blend
those somehow, and come up

00:53:32.180 --> 00:53:33.540
with a mosaic.

00:53:33.540 --> 00:53:36.200
And the funny part about
it is, 500 years from now,

00:53:36.200 --> 00:53:39.099
you can still have as
divided a viewpoint over what

00:53:39.099 --> 00:53:40.390
that history is, as you do now.

00:53:40.390 --> 00:53:40.640
Right?

00:53:40.640 --> 00:53:42.348
The ones who say, well
that MSNBC version

00:53:42.348 --> 00:53:43.886
is much more close to the truth.

00:53:43.886 --> 00:53:45.260
And I think maybe
that's the part

00:53:45.260 --> 00:53:47.570
that people listening to the
podcast found most interesting,

00:53:47.570 --> 00:53:48.720
was that there isn't just--

00:53:48.720 --> 00:53:49.970
I mean, that history's
not like math.

00:53:49.970 --> 00:53:50.420
Right?

00:53:50.420 --> 00:53:51.290
Two plus two equals four.

00:53:51.290 --> 00:53:52.373
The Roman Empire did this.

00:53:52.373 --> 00:53:55.040
And it isn't like that, because
it's composed of human beings,

00:53:55.040 --> 00:53:56.030
and we're variable.

00:53:56.030 --> 00:53:56.530
Right?

00:53:56.530 --> 00:53:59.000
And open to interpretation.

00:53:59.000 --> 00:54:00.140
Hard to quantify.

